coreInfo.description:
Event stores are database management systems implementing the concept of event sourcing. 
They persist all state changing events for an object together with a timestamp, thereby creating time series for individual objects. The current state of an object can be inferred by replaying all events for that object from time 0 till the current time. IBM® Db2 Event Store is an memory optimized database designed for massive structured data volumes and real-time analytics built on Apache SPARK and Apache Parquet Data Format.
coreInfo.label: Event Store

coreInfo.description: A consolidated repository of integrated, conformed, and aggregated data from multiple and disparate data sources in support of business analytics and reporting. Data warehouses typically process structured data in tabular/relational form, often with history, on scalable relational database technology platforms that support large numbers of concurrent users and complex queries across large data sets.
coreInfo.label: Data Warehouse

coreInfo.description: Enterprise business events is  produced throughout a business enterprise. At the edges of the enterprise, business events can be detected by sensors. In the enterprise network, business events can be produced when business processes start and complete or fail. The activity of the enterprise and its business can be monitored and changed as a result of events.
coreInfo.label: Enterprise Events

coreInfo.description: Technology that connects all of these data sources into a single self-balancing constellation. No longer are analytics queries performed on data copied and stored to a centralized location. The analytics application submits a query that is processed on the device where the data source is persisted. Results of the query are consolidated within the constellation, and returned to the origin application. No data is copied and remains persisted only at source.
coreInfo.label: Data Virtualization

coreInfo.description: Enterprises have their core applications to run the business transactions. Organizations also use the supporting applications like human resources, accounting, finance to support the core business of an enterprise
coreInfo.label: Support App

coreInfo.description: Marketing component provides capabilities to get deeper insights that help in making smarter marketing decisions, to drive results with personalized customer experiences across all channels,  to drive lasting loyalty with exceptional end-to-end customer experiences and to boost engagement and conversions wherever the customers are with SMS, push notifications and more.
coreInfo.label: Marketing

coreInfo.description: Supply chain management is the handling of the entire production flow of a good or service — starting from the raw components all the way to delivering the final product to the consumer. To accomplish this task, a company will create a network of suppliers (the “links” in the chain) that move the product along from the suppliers of raw materials to the organizations who deal directly with users.
coreInfo.label: Supply Chain

coreInfo.description: Core Applications drive the business transactions of an enterprise. Examples of core applications would include core banking, claims management, order management, ERP systems, transportation Systems, logistics management etc. Core applications is different for different industries
coreInfo.label: Core App

coreInfo.description: Digital, cross channel, social, and sentiment analytics**: collects data on customer behavior across channels to personalize shopping interaction.
coreInfo.label: Commerce

coreInfo.description: Business operations include a set of processes, applications and tools aimed at optimizing the harvested value from all assets owned by a business. This includes physical assets as well as other assets such as intellectual property.
coreInfo.label: Business Ops

coreInfo.description: A tool that uses powerful analytics to solve planning and scheduling challenges by reducing the effort, time, and risk associated with creating tailored solutions that improve business outcomes.
coreInfo.label: Decision Optimization

coreInfo.description: Operations handles the integration, usage, and delivery of key services to business applications and the enterprise, whether it is participating in incident management, architectural patterns, deployment, or other functions. Operations integrates with or drives key processes to ensure that the enterprise achieves its KPIs. It includes processes to recommend best practice for requirements analysis, planning, design, deployment, and ongoing operations management and technical support of cloud-based applications. Capabilities include runbook, dashboard, and collaboration.
coreInfo.label: Operations

coreInfo.description: The client or request fulfillment system reports an incident, requests a change, or seeks the status of an application. Service management users interact with clients or request fulfillment systems to gather more information if needed to diagnose incidents.
coreInfo.label: Request Fulfillment

coreInfo.description: Applications  become more powerful with prediction and optimization from AI and span various domains such as marketing, finance, healthcare, automotive, media, utilities or agriculture. These applications build upon trusted AI models and often take advantage of packaged automates tools to simplify and democratize AI deployments.
coreInfo.label: AI Apps

coreInfo.description: Assistant is an application for conversational AI agents that integrate across multiple channels and devices to help improve self-service and experience for customers and employees.
coreInfo.label: Assistant

coreInfo.description: Getting Weather Data from reliable data sources
coreInfo.label: Weather

coreInfo.description: Infrastructure resources used to run workloads.
coreInfo.label: Compute

coreInfo.description: Manages compute, network, and storage virtual resources provided by the lower layer. It also provides consolidation services to the upper layers for operational services.
coreInfo.label: Infrastructure Management

coreInfo.description: Tools and offerings that makes it easy to visualize, analyze, and share insights about your business.  They help you prepare and share data, uncover what drives performance, visualize that performance, and share those insights with your team via dashboards and pixel perfect reports.  While planning harnesses a powerful calculation engine to provide deep insights and automate planning, budgeting, and forecasting across lines of business with a single source of truth.
coreInfo.label: Reporting & Dashboarding

coreInfo.description: A data preparation capability in support of self-service analytics that allows quick transformation of large amountcs of raw data into consumable, quality information that is ready for analytics.
coreInfo.label: Data Refinery

coreInfo.description: Automated deployment of apps, middleware, test data, and utilities to test and production environments on demand.
coreInfo.label: Continuous Deployment

coreInfo.description: Team members and stakeholders continually communicate plans, tasks, issues, and feedback.
coreInfo.label: Collaborative Development

coreInfo.description: Applies cognitive analytics to social data to provide personality and social characteristics.
coreInfo.label: Actionable Insight

coreInfo.description: Includes the application and the options for the application's runtime environment, security, management, and release requirements.
coreInfo.label: Application

coreInfo.description: Binary files and other output from the build are sent to and managed in a build artifact repository.
coreInfo.label: Artifact Management

coreInfo.description: Tools used to write source code to implement the architecture.
coreInfo.label: Code Editor

coreInfo.description: Test cases are executed automatically and continuously after deployments have completed in production-like circumstances.
coreInfo.label: Continous Testing

coreInfo.description: A database technology that provides storage and retrieval of data modeled in a means other than the tabular relations of a relational database management system (RDBMS). NoSQL databases may support SQL-like query languages ("Not only SQL") and often support data in structured, semi-structured, and unstructured form. Most NoSQL databases implement a model of eventual consistency vs transactional consistency offered by relational database technologies.
coreInfo.label: NOSQL

coreInfo.description: The set of artifacts used to train the conversation API.
coreInfo.label: Ground Truth

coreInfo.description: Allows data scientists, developers, and retail business domain experts to drive improved business results and customer experience through the infusion of AI. Enables you to securely use your own data, and to use licensed and public external data in a governed fashion to create, train, and deploy self-learning models.
coreInfo.label: AI Services

coreInfo.description: Enables conversion from voice-based speech to text before invoking other APIs or processing.
coreInfo.label: Speech to Text

coreInfo.description: Leverages cognitive linguistic analysis to identify a variety of tones at both the sentence and document level. This insight can be used to refine and improve communications.
coreInfo.label: Tone Analyzer

coreInfo.description: Enables conversion from voice-based speech to text before invoking other APIs or processing.
coreInfo.label: Text to Speech

coreInfo.description: Enables creating virtual agents and bots that combine machine learning, natural language understanding, and integrated dialog tools to provide automated customer engagements. Provides an easy-to-use graphical environment to create natural conversation flows between your applications and your users.
coreInfo.label: Conversation

coreInfo.description: Stores answers to be provided to the user once the intent and entities have been understood. It also can include references or links to multimedia content.
coreInfo.label: Answer Storage

coreInfo.description: Includes object and file based storage delivered as a service to store content that is moved from the enterprise network to cloud. Provides capability to encrypt the content that is moved to the cloud.
coreInfo.label: Content Storage

coreInfo.description: Includes business processes that are executed to run the customer's business.
coreInfo.label: Business Process

coreInfo.description: Rule engine technology, decision service management, and rule management and governance support the definition of the decision and conversation flow, taking into account business data.
coreInfo.label: Decision System

coreInfo.description: Orchestrates the service request between the customer and the conversation, retrieve and rank, and the other APIs in the enterprise or public domain. Controls the flow of the business logic from the query to the end of the conversation.
coreInfo.label: AI Application Logic

coreInfo.description: Combines machine learning, natural language understanding, and entity extraction.
coreInfo.label: Natural Language Understanding

coreInfo.description: Multicloud Management is an integrated framework to monitor, govern, manage and optimize of multiple workloads across multiple cloud providers.
coreInfo.label: Multi Cloud Management

coreInfo.description: Supports customer care across the entire transaction lifecycle and all commerce channels, where customer care personnel can see the behaviors of a customer in more than one channel. Includes CRM and loyalty management. In most instances these core systems store transaction data.
coreInfo.label: Customer Service

coreInfo.description: Companies outsource marketing functions to third party cloud based marketing providers that provide end to end capabilities for creating, managing, personalizing and optimizing  Omani-channel campaigns .
coreInfo.label: 3rd Party Marketing Cloud

coreInfo.description: Server that is specialized to run certain applications; also known as runtime.
coreInfo.label: App Server

coreInfo.label: App Server_LC

coreInfo.description: Program or tool whose source code is openly published in order to use free of charge.
coreInfo.label: Open Source Tools

coreInfo.description: Enables lookup of available microservices.
coreInfo.label: Service Discovery & Configuration

coreInfo.description: Running instance of your code inside of a container.
coreInfo.label: Microservices

coreInfo.label: Microservices_LC

coreInfo.description: Provides an unstructured cloud data store to build and deliver cost-effective applications and services with high reliability and fast speed to market. IBM Cloud users can store and access unstructured data content and can interactively compose and connect to applications and services.
coreInfo.label: Backup/DR

coreInfo.description: Provides a centralized library domain with the ability to store, manage, access and secure any of type of digital content.
coreInfo.label: Centralized Content Repository

coreInfo.description: Performs the function of a metadata catalog file where you define centralized content repository schema. The catalog stores, manages, and provides access control for objects stored within the repository.
coreInfo.label: Library Catalog

coreInfo.description: One root cause can affect many services and applications, generating an alert for each affected component. The result is that too many people or the wrong people participate in the incident-management process and ultimately address only the symptoms. Also, too many less-relevant alerts can distract from the critical alerts. To handle these concerns, add an event-management capability to the toolchain to gather related events and show causal events rather than symptoms. An event-correlation tool can correlate events from monitoring sources. The tool consolidates millions of alerts across managed solutions and enterprise applications to a few actionable alerts. The first-responder team investigates correlated events to narrow down the issue. For complex issues, the incident owner and subject matter experts collaborate on the investigation and resolution.
coreInfo.label: Event Correlation

coreInfo.description: After the service is restored, problem management investigates the root cause of the problem by using techniques such as "5 Whys". When you understand what went wrong, take counter measures to prevent the incident from happening again. Capabilities include root cause analysis, incident analysis, and aspects of incident management.
coreInfo.label: Problem Management

coreInfo.description: Responsible for maintaining the cloud services and environment. Cloud platform administrators, operators, and managers.
coreInfo.label: Cloud Admin

coreInfo.description: A user or user agent.
coreInfo.label: User

coreInfo.description: Incident management restores the service as quickly as possible by using a first-responder team that is equipped with automation and well-defined runbooks. To maintain the best possible levels of service quality and availability, it performs sophisticated monitoring to detect issues early, before the service is affected. For complex incidents, subject matter experts collaborate on the investigation and resolution. Stakeholders, such as the application owner, are continuously informed about the status of the incident. Capabilities include event correlation, monitoring, log monitoring, collaboration, notification, dashboard, and runbooks.
coreInfo.label: Incident Management

coreInfo.description: Create a change request to address the root cause of the incident. The change request can be for the application, the infrastructure, or the supporting environment. Prioritize and approve changes, then add them to the backlog to be addressed in an agile manner. Ensure that standardized methods and procedures are used for efficient handling of all changes. Capabilities include backlog, develop, test, approve, and change.
coreInfo.label: Change Management

coreInfo.description: Third-party users gain access to the provider cloud or the enterprise network through edge services.
coreInfo.label: Cloud User

coreInfo.description: Person or automated system that makes use of one or more end-user applications.
coreInfo.label: IoT User

coreInfo.description: The disaster recovery administrator is responsible for maintaining the cloud services.
coreInfo.label: DR Admin

coreInfo.description: Accesses resources on premises or via a secure virtual private network (VPN).
coreInfo.label: Enterprise User

coreInfo.description: Software development method to bring Development and Operations closer.

coreInfo.description: The release is scheduled. The team needs tools that support release communication and managing, preparing, and deploying releases.

coreInfo.description: Build, scan, test, integrate, and package applications before deploying. Automates builds and deployments to the cloud.
coreInfo.label: Build. Test & Continous Integration

coreInfo.description: Prioritizes list of problems for resolution.
coreInfo.label: Prioritization

coreInfo.description: Tools used to diagnose the problem.
coreInfo.label: Service Management Tooling

coreInfo.description: Incorporates change requests into the change management pipeline.
coreInfo.label: Backlog/Change Request

coreInfo.description: Identifies the root cause of the problem.
coreInfo.label: 5 Why Analysis

coreInfo.description: Records incidents that are received, both resolved and unresolved, in the form of tickets. Performs trends analysis for related tickets over a period of time. As part of ensuring infrastructure availability and reliability, the site reliability engineer performs timely trending analysis of resolved tickets to determine if there are incidents that are occurring frequently and to define the issue's impact. The site reliability engineer relates similar tickets to an issue ticket and creates a problem record for further review and root cause analysis.
coreInfo.label: Ticketing & Trending

coreInfo.description: Log files are an important way to understand the status of applications and services. Monitor and analyze structured or unstructured logs by using elastic search of support-managed solutions or enterprise applications to identify patterns that require intervention or provide insight.
coreInfo.label: Log Monitoring

coreInfo.description: A notification system alerts on-call personnel based on notification rules for the triggered incidents. Notification systems create collaboration channels with alerts that are specific to an incident so that the incident owner and subject matter experts can have records within the incident investigation and mitigation. When an abnormal state is identified, people must be notified. Alerting can be done through email, SMS, or text message, and can consider assignments, vacation plans, and escalation. IBM Cloud provides options to implement alerting based on either IBM or third-party solutions.
coreInfo.label: Notification

coreInfo.description: Script-based operational tasks are defined, built, orchestrated, automated, and managed as runbooks. The first-responder team is equipped with automation and well-defined runbooks to resolve issues instantly. The automated process also updates the status of the event so that the dashboard, notification, and collaboration channels are synchronized. A key aspect of incident management is to restore the service as quickly as possible. Automated tasks can usually complete these steps faster than any administrator. To enhance the toolchain for incident management, include automated mitigation actions that are run after a defined alert is received. If no mitigation action is defined, automation can help in the investigation phase by taking a snapshot of critical system states, such as process lists and trace routes. A less-intrusive precursor to automation is detailed documentation of the steps to take. Runbooks guide the administrator through those steps. When people are more comfortable with the process, the invocation can be changed to a semi-automatic or fully automated mode.
coreInfo.label: Runbook

coreInfo.description: Records analyzed known issues for history.
coreInfo.label: Known Error Database

coreInfo.description: Knowing the current state of the services that are offered to users is a key requirement. Dashboards provide both the current state and the historical progression of the associated metrics. Ideally, dashboards combine views of the IT aspects and the business aspects so that the incident owner can quickly relate them. The dashboard is preconfigured to provide one view of various sources of events from event correlation and monitoring systems. This view guides the first responder and subject matter experts to isolate and resolve issues through runbooks.
coreInfo.label: Dashboard

coreInfo.description: Script-based operational tasks are defined, built, orchestrated, automated, and managed as runbooks. The first-responder team is equipped with automation and well-defined runbooks to resolve issues instantly. The automated process also updates the status of the event so that the dashboard, notification, and collaboration channels are synchronized. A key aspect of incident management is to restore the service as quickly as possible. Automated tasks can usually complete these steps faster than any administrator. To enhance the toolchain for incident management, include automated mitigation actions that are run after a defined alert is received. If no mitigation action is defined, automation can help in the investigation phase by taking a snapshot of critical system states, such as process lists and trace routes. A less-intrusive precursor to automation is detailed documentation of the steps to take. Runbooks guide the administrator through those steps. When people are more comfortable with the process, the invocation can be changed to a semi-automatic or fully automated mode.
coreInfo.label: Runbooks

coreInfo.description: Collects statistics about user experience quality to enable the operator to act on service degradation.

coreInfo.description: The service for the IBM Cloud console that people use to connect to blockchain service running on public IBM Cloud using a browser.
coreInfo.label: Provider Cloud Portal Service

coreInfo.description: Guides and automates data analysis, discovery, and visualization on mobile devices.
coreInfo.label: Device Analytics

coreInfo.description: Real-time ingest, process, transform, augment, and analytics of the telematics data
coreInfo.label: Streaming Computing

coreInfo.description: Copies and correlates information from disparate sources to produce meaningful associations related to primary business dimensions.
coreInfo.label: Data Integration

coreInfo.description: Guides and automates data analysis, discovery, and visualization.
coreInfo.label: Analytics

coreInfo.description: Provides the persistence layers to power the cloud app to store, collaborate, visualize, share, and gain insights from data.
coreInfo.label: Data Service

coreInfo.description: Provides access to the user profiles for both cloud users and enterprise users. A user profile provides a login account and lists the resources (data sets, APIs, and other services) that the individual is authorized to access.

coreInfo.description: Provides devices or applications that store info, data, and more in the form of files.

Usually associated with Hadoop-oriented object storage in which a retailer's data is loaded into the Hadoop platform, and business analytics, data mining, and AI tools are applied to the data.

coreInfo.label: Peer Services

coreInfo.description: An IBM Cloud service captures alerts.
coreInfo.label: Event Feed

coreInfo.description: Asynchronous communication among cloud applications and components.

coreInfo.description: Supports orchestration of services, user interface, and front end for backend pattern.

coreInfo.description: Lets users explore and interact with data from the data repositories and actionable insight applications or enterprise applications.
coreInfo.label: Visualization

coreInfo.description: Applications that accomplish business goals and objectives and that may interact with cloud services.
coreInfo.label: Enterprise Applications

coreInfo.description: A mobile app is downloaded on the mobile device. A mobile device management agent is installed on the mobile device. Client-side libraries provided by IBM Cloudant are on the mobile device that enable offline capabilities for storing the information in a disconnected mode. The information stored on the device is encrypted.
coreInfo.label: Mobile App

coreInfo.description:
This icon library can assist architects to rapidly build IT System View diagrams that are consistent with the icons and backgrounds in reference architectures and solution architectures in the public IBM Cloud Architecture Center (https://www.ibm.com/cloud/garage/architectures).

This asset contains:

  • A set of IT System Views, each of which represent a commonly-used background.  You can copy a background first in its entirety into your new diagram and then edit them, if necessary.

  • One IT System View, "All Icons By Category", contains the current, standard node icons, with their standard descriptions.  You can copy and paste from this view into your diagram so that your architecture reuses these standard node icons, names and descriptions. 

We will periodically update this icon template library to add more icons and make other improvements.

For feedback on this asset, please use the Cognitive Architect Slack channel

https://ibm-sales.slack.com/messages/C7TJYT0AE

Visit the IBM Architectural Center at:
https://www.ibm.com/cloud/garage/architectures
V 1.0, April 30, 2018
